<section>
  <h1>Secret area — HTTP Basic Auth</h1>

  <% if (authed) { %>
    <p class="lede">✅ You're in. Your browser sent an
      <code>Authorization: Basic</code> header.</p>
    <h2>What the wire carried</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Header value: <code>Basic <%= encoded %></code></li>
      <li>Base64-decoded: <code><%= decoded %></code></li>
    </ul>
    <p class="tip">That's it — no decryption, just Base64. Anyone capturing the
      packet reads your credentials by decoding that string.</p>
  <% } else { %>
    <p class="lede">
      This page is protected by <strong>HTTP Basic Auth</strong>. When you
      request it, the server replies <code>401</code> with
      <code>WWW-Authenticate: Basic</code>, your browser prompts, then retries
      with an <code>Authorization: Basic …</code> header.
    </p>
    <p class="tip">Demo credentials (fake): <code><%= basicUser %></code> /
      <code><%= basicPass %></code>. Reload and enter them in the browser prompt.</p>
  <% } %>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>Capture this</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Display filter: <code>http.authorization</code> (or <code>http.request.uri == "/secret"</code>)</li>
    <li>Find the request carrying <code>Authorization: Basic &lt;base64&gt;</code>.</li>
    <li>Wireshark even shows the decoded <em>Credentials</em> field under the
      Authorization header — or decode it yourself: it's just
      <code>base64("user:pass")</code>.</li>
    <li>Lesson: Base64 is <strong>encoding, not encryption</strong>. Only HTTPS
      actually hides this.</li>
  </ul>
</section>
